<p>Slovenia’s bollards are similar but always have a white back reflector, whereas in Austria, white reflectors are rare but possible.</p>', 'Description and images taken from:  <a href="https://www.plonkit.net/austria" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">www.plonkit.net/austria</a>.', '["https://learnablemeta.com/images/ULJUElQw5CIdWIGkDCBoMOxikLh8haOBJZfz.avif"]', '{"country":"Austria","metaName":"Bollard","note":"<p>Austria''s bollards are white with a black top and dark red or grey reflectors, often featuring a nipple-shaped black cap and sometimes a snow pole.</p>\n<p>Slovenia’s bollards are similar but always have a white back reflector, whereas in Austria, white reflectors are rare but possible.</p>","images":["https://learnablemeta.com/images/ULJUElQw5CIdWIGkDCBoMOxikLh8haOBJZfz.avif"],"footer":"Description and images taken from:  <a href=\"https://www.plonkit.net/austria\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">www.plonkit.net/austria</a>."}', '2025-08-01 19:32:50', '2025-08-01 19:32:50');
<p>Estonian bollards might look similar, but they have a rounded shape and will never have numbers on them.</p>', 'Check out  <a href="https://www.plonkit.net/latvia" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">www.plonkit.net/latvia</a> for more clues.', '["https://learnablemeta.com/images/1/dc0gvNIKVbMEQc4ZoJQOVKwY75cPq8dojJ1F.avif","https://learnablemeta.com/images/1/cICSrBKIcnMjNHLLrnKxrAhIiyBjp74yGoFV.avif"]', '{"country":"Latvia","metaName":"Bollard","note":"<p>Half-circle/flat curved shape bollards with a rectangular reflector on the front and two circular reflectors on the back are common. The reflectors can be white or orange, and sometimes these bollards have numbers on them.</p>\n<p>Estonian bollards might look similar, but they have a rounded shape and will never have numbers on them.</p>","images":["https://learnablemeta.com/images/1/dc0gvNIKVbMEQc4ZoJQOVKwY75cPq8dojJ1F.avif","https://learnablemeta.com/images/1/cICSrBKIcnMjNHLLrnKxrAhIiyBjp74yGoFV.avif"],"footer":"Check out  <a href=\"https://www.plonkit.net/latvia\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">www.plonkit.net/latvia</a> for more clues."}', '2025-08-01 19:36:17', '2025-08-01 19:36:17');
<p>NOTE: Many European countries have similar bollards, however most will have different coloured reflectors. Luxembourg uses almost identical bollards, but they have 3 bolts instead of 2 on the reflector.</p>', 'Description and images taken from:  <a href="https://www.plonkit.net/germany" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">www.plonkit.net/germany</a>.', '["https://learnablemeta.com/images/9TCEY8VN4NT1vJLX6ktdeYAHVVuUhvNlHRNr.avif","https://learnablemeta.com/images/1/bMXHJgWEBhouzs7sQJFdyaObZGNxjdK2rLZf.avif"]', '{"country":"Germany","metaName":"Bollard","note":"<p>Germany uses these black and white bollards, with white and light-grey reflectors. The reflector will be orange on bollards next to intersections. They sometimes have plates containing the road number, and potentially other useful information. Many bollards also feature blue attachments on the side.</p>\n<p>NOTE: Many European countries have similar bollards, however most will have different coloured reflectors. Luxembourg uses almost identical bollards, but they have 3 bolts instead of 2 on the reflector.</p>","images":["https://learnablemeta.com/images/9TCEY8VN4NT1vJLX6ktdeYAHVVuUhvNlHRNr.avif","https://learnablemeta.com/images/1/bMXHJgWEBhouzs7sQJFdyaObZGNxjdK2rLZf.avif"],"footer":"Description and images taken from:  <a href=\"https://www.plonkit.net/germany\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">www.plonkit.net/germany</a>."}', '2025-08-01 19:39:55', '2025-08-01 19:39:55');
<p>This word is almost entirely unique to Lithuanian, though very rarely, you might see "gatve" (abbreviated as "gat.") in the Latvian capital, Riga.</p>', 'Description and images taken from:  <a href="https://www.plonkit.net/lithuania" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">www.plonkit.net/lithuania</a>.', '["https://learnablemeta.com/images/ehjY0xFvN0XFpuwFZJNoFwbFoBT4I9B1N9oS.avif"]', '{"country":"Lithuania","metaName":"Street name ending - g.","note":"<p>The Lithuanian word for street is \"gatvė,\" often abbreviated as \"g.\" on street signs. If you see a street sign ending in \"g.,\" you''re likely in Lithuania.</p>\n<p>This word is almost entirely unique to Lithuanian, though very rarely, you might see \"gatve\" (abbreviated as \"gat.\") in the Latvian capital, Riga.</p>","images":["https://learnablemeta.com/images/ehjY0xFvN0XFpuwFZJNoFwbFoBT4I9B1N9oS.avif"],"footer":"Description and images taken from:  <a href=\"https://www.plonkit.net/lithuania\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">www.plonkit.net/lithuania</a>."}', '2025-08-01 19:47:44', '2025-08-01 19:47:44');
